    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "image",
      "title": "Image",
      "uuid": "4f9967d8b65a4a73a9ffb9960332fb12",
      "x": 16189.905813610694,
      "y": 8200.098739743686,
      "width": 436.7248159853334,
      "height": 698.1580577932709,
      "z_value": -9.970000000000017,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "image_b64": "",
      "cache_key": "44f2cddb49ae75d97053f468bde0bb7030a9ddbb5568de875a500eeccbf8aa59.jpg",
      "caption": "2022-03-16 15.03.03",
      "source_path": "C:\\Users\\thisg\\Desktop\\Cloning Humans\\Images\\2022-03-16 15.03.03.jpg",
      "source_size": 271945,
      "source_mtime": 1769551590.6615517,
      "show_border": true,
      "depth_front": false
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "253ffd8db19f4364a7f33a716b1afeb9",
      "x": 31065.5567772397,
      "y": 9157.079877611373,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.596000000000224,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "As fixes land in the right sequence, the chain progressively self-rebalances. Each cleared friction point reduces compensatory load on adjacent nodes, which in turn shrinks the effective size of their bottlenecks. The chain \"sanitizes\" \u2014 meaning the modular profiles of adjacent nodes converge toward matched throughput, aligned tempo, compatible practice, overlapping tolerance, and balanced headroom. Symbiosis is the steady-state where every node's functional form is shaped by and shapes its neighbors without imposed friction."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "If we constantly only read things about previous things we did",
      "uuid": "9d411f74d27e404a822410d2fa45a637",
      "x": -229.28428829751397,
      "y": -589.0088472594618,
      "width": 648.5,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.958000000000023,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "If we constantly only read things about previous things we did",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9e8ffb4c07fa4bdaa9618688bcb22962",
      "x": 33990.91552260799,
      "y": 12010.446627625157,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.575000000000236,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Standalone market viability \u2014 does this node, considered in isolation, exist in a macroeconomic environment that supports it? Demand curves, factor costs, labor markets, capital availability, regulatory regime \u2014 all assessed for the node alone, not for its contribution to the chain.\nSectoral macro exposure \u2014 what macro forces (inflation sensitivity, currency exposure, commodity dependence, interest-rate sensitivity, trade policy exposure) act on this node independently of the chain it serves?\nEndogenous economic health \u2014 would this node be operationally and financially viable if the chain didn't exist? This separates nodes that are carried by the chain from nodes that are genuinely productive units.\nMacro tailwind/headwind vector \u2014 is the node's standalone environment improving, stable, or deteriorating on its own trajectory? A node in a structurally declining standalone market is a different prioritization candidate than one in a structurally growing one, even if their current chain contribution is identical.\nThe rating multiplier"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "0f2767cb6d2c4462a1638a8dfa07b6c1",
      "x": 33804.77251946935,
      "y": 10996.657341376045,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.574000000000236,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Each node receives a singleton economic rating \u2014 a multiplier applied to the gain/effort/risk output of the rest of the Phase 1 chain. Conceptually:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "19b769bff5c847febff82c1b5e5023f1",
      "x": 37671.565646306175,
      "y": 13072.98695928794,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.553000000000248,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Show more\nApr 27\nClaude responded: Right \u2014 and now the framework reads completely differently.\nRight \u2014 and now the framework reads completely differently. It's not a project-management tool dressed up in abstraction; it's a life-applicator, and the structure follows from that origin in a way that's actually elegant."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Bloom",
      "uuid": "d0312e7684b04ec6b3f21d30f6a1db9b",
      "x": 13031.907963457097,
      "y": 5168.103213772524,
      "width": 594.716934060388,
      "height": 702.4828568256082,
      "z_value": -9.918000000000045,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The full chain from empty tab to \"Intricate\" showing up:\n1. Get a code signing certificate\nSelf-signed (free, for learning the process): New-SelfSignedCertificate in PowerShell, won't be trusted by other machines\nPaid CA (for real distribution): DigiCert, Sectigo, GlobalSign \u2014 roughly $200-400/year for standard, $400+ for EV (Extended Validation, required for SmartScreen reputation on day one)\nAzure Trusted Signing (newer, cheaper): ~$10/month, Microsoft acts as the CA, handles the HSM requirement that EV certs now mandate\n2. Sign with signtool.exe\nsigntool sign /fd SHA256 /tr http://timestamp.digicert.com /td SHA256 /f certificate.pfx /p password about_node.ico\n\nThat populates the Embedded Signatures tab. The /tr timestamp means the signature stays valid after the cert expires.\n3. What gets signed in the MSI pipeline\nSign each .exe and .dll first (pythonw.exe wrapper, any .pyd like the Rust logger)\nThe .ico files CAN be signed but typically aren't \u2014 they travel inside the signed MSI/EXE\nSign the .msi itself last\nThe MSI signature is what Windows, SmartScreen, and UAC actually check\n4. The realistic path for Intricate\nThe icons don't need individual signatures \u2014 they're embedded resources inside the signed installer\nWhat matters is: signed .msi \u2192 signed .exe entry point \u2192 SmartScreen trusts it\nThe ICO Digital Signatures tab is interesting but it's the MSI and EXE signatures that gate the user experience\nSo the short answer: that tab will say \"Intricate\" when you run signtool sign against the file with a certificate whose Subject CN is \"Intricate\". But in practice, you'd sign the MSI and the frozen EXE, not the individual icons.\nWorth doing a dry run with a self-signed cert to see the full flow before spending money on a real one. Want me to generate one and sign an icon as a proof of concept?"
    },
    {
