      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "The only known photo of Eddie",
      "depth_front": true,
      "node_tint": "#8a7560"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Clippy, Blessed be his name",
      "uuid": "80b1c9c1fc7a49e3abba134db5f142d2",
      "x": 14311.135585894177,
      "y": 5272.373150108695,
      "width": 296.10427007409885,
      "height": 48.41869934744955,
      "z_value": -9.989000000000006,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Clippy, Blessed be his name",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": "#2a3a2f"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Note",
      "uuid": "e1aa656283bc43f6b89847aee23c5794",
      "x": 4623.108724497274,
      "y": 3377.9298985807823,
      "width": 68.0,
      "height": 30.0,
      "z_value": -9.662000000000187,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Good",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "claude_response",
      "title": "Response",
      "uuid": "20b7f6c4bc964eccac6955d5b5162c6d",
      "x": 17641.025402546926,
      "y": 2819.867859609696,
      "width": 420.0,
      "height": 204.0,
      "z_value": -9.702000000000165,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "label": "Now it's vertically centred within the button zone strip \u2014 same row height as the tint/depth/close buttons, tucked into the right corner.",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c518d76c073b46a0b6ef7be91b570923",
      "x": 28645.951976819673,
      "y": 3375.069706805176,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.62000000000021,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Capacity bottlenecks \u2014 surfaced at Layer 2 peak comparison. Demand will exceed peak handling.\nThroughput bottlenecks \u2014 surfaced at Layer 2 average comparison. The chain can't sustain steady-state flow even if it can spike.\nNode bottlenecks \u2014 surfaced at Layer 3. Specific hubs whose handling times are disproportionate to their share of load.\nPractice bottlenecks \u2014 surfaced at Layer 4. A node has the physical capacity but lacks the operational practice to use it.\nWhat to do with this"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3f640b1a4f6443d389d7a63e70aba725",
      "x": 28509.138601922114,
      "y": 2324.5405964316246,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.62200000000021,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Layer 1 (historical vs. potential growth) sets the baseline gap \u2014 it tells you whether the system has historically underperformed its ceiling, and why. That \"why\" (constraint type per era) is your hypothesis library for what could constrain things again.\nLayer 2 (future demand vs. peak vs. supply chain average) is where structural bottlenecks first surface. The key move is the double comparison: peak demand exposes capacity bottlenecks, but comparing against supply chain average load (not goods' average) exposes throughput bottlenecks \u2014 the steady-state ones that don't show up in capacity planning.\nLayer 3 (top 10 destination hubs + handling times) geolocates the bottleneck. Handling time per hub is the diagnostic signal \u2014 outliers here are your concentrated failure points.\nLayer 4 (practices per link/node) lets you classify each bottleneck as either practice-solvable (operational fix) or structural (needs investment / redesign).\nWhere bottlenecks emerge when you read it forward"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "e310088dbecb442283dc55619f980720",
      "x": 28419.027201020388,
      "y": 2650.708371202153,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.62100000000021,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Three categories fall out naturally:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "004a06493dba4107aa7561f88601966c",
      "x": 29165.723890997073,
      "y": 3952.4277548911723,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.618000000000212,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Want to apply this to a specific good or sector, or keep it abstract for now?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "fa875c243e494f82afc8298de52f0b1d",
      "x": 28980.922516429444,
      "y": 3422.3504279041235,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.619000000000211,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The useful question at each layer is: \"What does this layer reveal that the previous one couldn't?\" If a bottleneck only shows up at Layer 3, it's geographic/node-specific. If it shows up at Layer 2 already, it's systemic. That distinction drives whether you fix it with local intervention or chain-wide redesign."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "4071a3b714894af0bf6beb09f82fcf87",
      "x": 29868.203469683893,
      "y": 4033.785115766528,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.616000000000213,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 27\nClaude responded: Got it \u2014 and the distinction matters.\nGot it \u2014 and the distinction matters. You're shifting from layered overview (where each phase narrows the whole system) to modular application (where the entire reasoning chain is run per node, treating each node as a self-contained system that also has to mesh with its neighbors)."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "87d715e0592442268764d1f218f2606f",
      "x": 29284.068380470937,
      "y": 5831.645855203813,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.612000000000215,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The layered approach told you where bottlenecks live. The modular approach tells you what each node actually is as a functional unit \u2014 its inputs, its conversion logic, its outputs, its tolerances. You get a per-node \"shape.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c52942aebdd449e4a40732309e0fe436",
      "x": 25583.123001722244,
      "y": -1608.0065275944166,
      "width": 319.2318687833322,
      "height": 237.62633011250546,
      "z_value": -9.6390000000002,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Historical population growth \u2014 measured against potential growth per context Key idea: compare actual trajectories to what was theoretically possible given each era's constraints (food, disease, tech, geography, social structure). The gap = the interesting part.\nPrimary goods and services \u2014 (awaiting your take)\nWhat angle here \u2014 the economic-sector sense (extraction/agriculture/raw materials), the Rawlsian \"primary goods\" sense (basic things any rational person would want), or something else?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "972d83c102ab4369998f5ab3e89f3164",
      "x": 30131.794061694785,
      "y": 4562.210548823428,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.615000000000213,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Modular application of the Phase 1 reasoning chain"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "98824082071a4349af293002e76dd021",
      "x": 25890.04378567614,
      "y": -65.8203468752572,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.635000000000202,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: And compare those load bearing limits with an estimated supply chain daily average load, rather than the average load of the goods themselves\nAnd compare those load bearing limits with an estimated supply chain daily average load, rather than the average load of the goods themselves"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "570d22291ba948a5b740948c71d483bc",
      "x": 25464.513388509597,
      "y": -982.0569301742062,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.6380000000002,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: Future demand of such measured against current daily peaks per demand\nFuture demand of such measured against current daily peaks per demand"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9e7844e4b0e5429fb9616c417f22870f",
      "x": 26135.099792497476,
      "y": 1217.5107266827654,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.630000000000205,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Historical population growth \u2014 measured against potential growth per context Key idea: compare actual trajectories to what was theoretically possible given each era's constraints (food, disease, tech, geography, social structure). The gap = the interesting part.\nPrimary goods and services \u2014 future demand vs. current daily peak demand, then vs. supply chain daily average load Key idea: project future demand for essentials and benchmark against today's peak-load capacity (not averages). Then compare those load-bearing limits against the supply chain's daily average load \u2014 not the goods' own average load. The supply chain itself is the binding constraint.\nMap to top 10 destination hotshots + estimated handling times per each Key idea: take the demand/supply-chain picture and overlay it onto the current top 10 destination hubs (the busiest nodes). For each, estimate handling time so you can see where throughput bottlenecks concentrate geographically \u2014 turns the abstract load analysis into a node-level diagnostic.\nKeep them coming."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "0b7f923545e4436eb59ebbee6f86d1e6",
      "x": 25804.15669288534,
      "y": -355.7076105879646,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.636000000000202,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Historical population growth \u2014 measured against potential growth per context Key idea: compare actual trajectories to what was theoretically possible given each era's constraints (food, disease, tech, geography, social structure). The gap = the interesting part.\nPrimary goods and services \u2014 future demand vs. current daily peak demand Key idea: project forward demand for essentials (food, water, energy, etc.) and benchmark it against today's peak-load capacity, not averages. Peaks expose where systems actually break.\nNext one?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b650afb3d7b8496d852b7dd31cff672d",
      "x": 25706.233105410018,
      "y": 185.13757182453992,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.632000000000204,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: Then map this to the current top ten destination hotshots with an estimate of handling times per each\nThen map this to the current top ten destination hotshots with an estimate of handling times per each"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "7e0ab295c81a4766b1f3e635ef6d02b5",
      "x": 25161.0849460305,
      "y": -45.130169723751806,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.633000000000203,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Historical population growth \u2014 measured against potential growth per context Key idea: compare actual trajectories to what was theoretically possible given each era's constraints (food, disease, tech, geography, social structure). The gap = the interesting part.\nPrimary goods and services \u2014 future demand vs. current daily peak demand, then vs. supply chain daily average load Key idea: project future demand for essentials and benchmark against today's peak-load capacity (not averages). Then compare those load-bearing limits against the supply chain's daily average load \u2014 not the goods' own average load. The supply chain itself is the binding constraint, and its steady-state throughput is what determines whether peaks can actually be met.\nReady for the next one whenever."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Left foot, right foot, left foot, right foot",
